{"title_page": "Everest College", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Everest College\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = \n| latin_name = \n| other_name =          <!-- or: | other_names = -->\n| former_name =         <!-- or: | former_names = -->\n| motto = \n| motto_lang = \n| mottoeng = \n| type = non-profit career school\n| established =         {{start date|2007}} \n| closed =              <!-- {{end date|YYYY}} -->\n| founder = [[Corinthian Colleges]]\n| parent = Zenith Education Group ([[Educational Credit Management Corporation]])\n| affiliation = \n| religious_affiliation =\n| academic_affiliation =\n| endowment = \n| budget = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| chairman = \n| chairperson = \n| chancellor = \n| president = \n| vice-president = \n| superintendent = \n| provost = \n| vice_chancellor= \n| rector = \n| principal = \n| dean = \n| director = \n| head_label = \n| head = \n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students = \n| undergrad = \n| postgrad = \n| doctoral = \n| other = \n| address =             <!-- Please discuss before using -->\n| city = \n| state = \n| province = \n| country = United States\n| postcode =            <!-- or: | postalcode = --><!-- or: | zipcode = -->\n| coor = \n| campus = \n| language = \n| free_label = \n| free = \n| colors =              <!-- or: | colours = -->\n| website =             {{URL|http://www.everest.edu}} \n| logo = \n| logo_size =\n| logo_alt =\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Everest College'''  is a system of colleges in the United States, and with [[Wyotech]], make up Zenith Education. It was until 2015 a system of [[for-profit college]]s in the United States and the Canadian province of Ontario, owned and operated by [[Corinthian Colleges, Inc.]] In 2015, Corinthian ceased operating and filed for bankruptcy. While most Corinthian-owned colleges were closed in early 2015, [[Educational Credit Management Corporation]] (ECMC), a non-profit, took ownership of more than half of Corinthian Colleges' campuses, including many Everest College campuses. As of 2016, 19 ECMC-owned Everest locations remain in operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everest.edu/locations/complete_list/|title=Careers Start Here - Altierus Career College|website=www.everest.edu|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> At least 10 more campuses were closed or in the process of closing in 2016.<ref name=\"acics.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acics.org/commission%20actions/content.aspx?id=1476 |title=Institution/Campus Closings |publisher=ACICS |date= |accessdate=2018-06-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/business/dp-tidewaterbiz-everest-20160408-story.html|title=Everest College in Newport News to close|first=Tara|last=Bozick|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/03/28/nonprofit-owner-former-corinthian-colleges-campuses-loses-100-million-while|title=Nonprofit owner of former Corinthian Colleges campuses loses $100 million while overhauling career college chain|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Canadian branches were not purchased by ECMC and remain closed.\n\nFollowing significant downsizing, Everest graduates still express concerns that their degrees are worthless.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pilotonline.com/trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-schools-revival/article_5e9e22de-47d2-56b5-bc6a-f37907160c5b.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316143617/http://pilotonline.com/trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-schools-revival/article_5e9e22de-47d2-56b5-bc6a-f37907160c5b.html |archive-date=2016-03-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Corinthian Colleges was compelled to pay more than $1.1 billion to the State of California, in part for defrauding thousands of students.   The judge ordered restitution of $820 million for students and civil penalties of $350 million.  According to the California State Attorney General \"For years, Corinthian profited off the backs of poor people\u2014now they have to pay. This judgment sends a clear message: There is a cost to this kind of predatory conduct.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-corinthian-colleges-judgment-false-advertising-20160323-story.html|title=Corinthian Colleges must pay nearly $1.2 billion for false advertising and lending practices|first=Matt|last=Hamilton|website=latimes.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nMore than a thousand former Everest College students have been afforded [[debt relief]] by the US government because of Everest's questionable business practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/12/04/debt-relief-some-former-corinthian-students|title=Debt Relief for Some Former Corinthian Students - Inside Higher Ed|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-85064397/|title=LA Times|website=touch.latimes.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2015/11/17/456367152/corinthian-misled-students-on-job-placement-investigation-finds|title=Corinthian Colleges Misled Students On Job Placement, Investigation Finds|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> Thousands more may get debt relief.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/education-dept-to-give-de_b_9544468.html|title=Education Dept to Give Debt Relief to More Corinthian Students|first=David|last=Halperin|date=25 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn 2007, Corinthian Colleges consolidated a number of schools under the Everest brand name. Former schools that became Everest Colleges include: [[Bryman College]], [[Ashmead College]], Mountain West College, Olympia College, [[Kee Business College]], Parks College, Western Business College, [[Blair College]] and [[Springfield College (Missouri)|Springfield College]]. In December 2007, Corinthian Colleges, Inc. (CCi) re-branded their Ontario campuses as Everest College and sold the remaining campus locations across Canada to the [[Eminata Group]].<ref>[http://investors.cci.edu/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=556063 CCI sells campuses to Eminata Group] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219224642/http://investors.cci.edu/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=556063 |date=2015-02-19 }} News Release Dec. 14, 2007</ref>\n\nIn [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], where a Corinthian Everest campus was financed with $11 million in city bonds, 25% of students found jobs and over half dropped out; the campus closed in 2012, two years after it opened.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Herzog|first1=Karen|title=University of Phoenix to close three state campuses|url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/university-of-phoenix-to-close-three-state-campuses-a379a0t-174864561.html|accessdate=19 February 2015|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=18 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prwatch.org/news/2013/07/12175/cashing-kids-139-alec-bills-2013-promote-private-profit-education-model|title=Cashing in on Kids: 139 ALEC Bills in 2013 Promote a Private, For-Profit Education Model|work=PR Watch|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe diplomas issued by Everest College were described as worthless as many graduated students found no job placement, the reputation tainted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Sophia|title=Everest College grads want loan forgiveness for 'worthless' diploma|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/everest-college-grads-want-loan-forgiveness-for-worthless-diploma-1.3036143|website=CBC News|accessdate=17 April 2015|ref=worthless_tainted}}</ref>\n\nThe Ontario government stepped in and shut down 14 Everest College of Business, Health Care and Technology campus locations owned by Corinthian Colleges on February 19, 2015. The next day, Everest College in Ontario, Canada declared bankruptcy.<ref name=everest_bankrupt>{{cite news|title=Everest College files for bankruptcy as other schools offer help|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/everest-college-files-for-bankruptcy-as-other-schools-offer-help-1.2965569|website=CBC News|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, [[Educational Credit Management Corporation]]'s subsidiary Zenith Education Group acquired 56 ''Everest College'' and [[WyoTech]] campuses from Corinthian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/02/04/guaranty-agency-buys-half-corinthian-colleges-and-forgives-480-million-student-debt|title=Guaranty agency buys half of Corinthian Colleges and forgives $480 million in student debt|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> Zenith planned to transition the schools from for-profit to nonprofit status. It also planned to eliminate some programs with poor completion and job placement rates.<ref name=\"wapo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2015/02/03/heres-how-a-debt-collector-plans-to-turn-around-failing-for-profit-colleges/|title=Here\u2019s how a debt collector plans to turn around failing for-profit colleges|last=Douglas-Gabriel|first=Danielle|date=3 February 2015 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref> Campuses with little to no revenue along with the 15 Everest campuses in California, which were not acquired by ECMC, closed their doors for good when Corinthian Colleges shuttered all of their remaining campuses on April 27, 2015.<ref name=\"kron4-0429\">{{cite news |last1=Sevilla |first1=Mario |date=April 29, 2015 |title=FAQS about Heald, Everest, And Wyotech Campuses |url=http://kron4.com/2015/04/29/faqs-about-heald-everest-and-wyotech-campuses/ |publisher=[[KRON-TV]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528155551/http://kron4.com/2015/04/29/faqs-about-heald-everest-and-wyotech-campuses |archivedate=2015-05-28 |url-status=live |accessdate=2015-06-09 |quote=[[Corinthian Colleges]] shut down all of its remaining 28 ground campuses on Monday, April 27, displacing 16,000 students. Hundreds of students were left with unfinished diplomas and loan debt. The shutdown comes less than two weeks after the [[U.S. Department of Education]] announcing it was fining the for-profit institution $30 million for misrepresentation.}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the US Department of Education fired Everest College's monitor, Hogan Marren Babbo & Rose Ltd., implicating several conflicts of interest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/news/politics/article/Trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-6888160.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322062631/http://www.sfchronicle.com/news/politics/article/Trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-6888160.php |archive-date=2016-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The State of California was also awarded $1.1 billion from Corinthian Colleges for false advertising and predatory business practices.<ref name=\"onebillion\">{{cite web |url=https://studentloansresolved.com/2019/03/07/everest-college-lawsuit-forgiveness-options/ |title=Everest College Lawsuit: What should borrowers know about forgiveness options |website=studentloansresolved.com |accessdate=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307192752/https://studentloansresolved.com/2019/03/07/everest-college-lawsuit-forgiveness-options/ |archive-date=7 March 2019 |date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The judge ordered restitution of $820 million for students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-86322238/|title=LA Times|website=touch.latimes.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 Associated Press investigation alleged that Everest still recruits through telemarketing, has yet to make significant changes to its shoddy curriculum. Recent graduates also reported being unable to find work that would allow them to pay their student loans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/fe5ef895b70d4b0ebecac9d5f6ab583a/trouble-remains-following-failed-profit-schools-revival|title=Trouble remains following failed for-profit schools' revival|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nApproximately 96% of Everest's funds come from the US government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/static.apps.cironline.org/doe/133.html|title=133 for-profit colleges get more than 90 percent of their revenue from taxpayers|website=s3.amazonaws.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> In 2016, ECMC, Everest's parent company, provided an infusion of capital to keep the schools running.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/07/28/zenith-education-gets-new-leader-250-million-it-seeks-turn-around-former-corinthian|title=Zenith Education gets a new leader, $250 million as it seeks to turn around former Corinthian programs|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Accreditation==\n\n[[Higher education accreditation in the United States|Accreditation]] for Everest College varies by country, state and region. Everest College campuses that are [[regional accreditation|regionally accredited]] are Everest College Phoenix, Everest College Mesa and online courses taught through Everest College Phoenix. All other Everest College campuses are [[Regional accreditation#Regional accreditation vs. national accreditation|nationally accredited]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everest.edu/accreditation|title=Everest: Accreditation Information|work=everest.edu|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nGenerally, credits from nationally accredited institutions are not transferable to other colleges and universities.<ref>[http://insidehighered.com/news/2007/02/26/transfer Tussling Over Transfer of Credit, ''[[Inside Higher Ed]]'', February 26, 2007 by Doug Lederman]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Everest College Phoenix was placed on academic probation by its accrediting body over concerns that it did not have enough autonomy and control over on-campus academics and operations from the parent company, Corinthian Colleges, Inc. In September 2010, the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]] rejected a recommendation from its evaluation panel that the school's accreditation be revoked outright. In November 2010 the Higher Learning Commission voted to place the campus on a \"Show-Cause\" status which will require the College to demonstrate to the commission why its accreditation should not be revoked. Everest College Phoenix had until March 2011 to respond to the request and the matter was not expected to be resolved until November 2011. The College remained an accredited institution during this period.<ref>\"[http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/business/articles/2010/11/17/20101117phoenix-everest-college-credentials-in-jeopardy.html Credentials of Everest College in jeopardy],\" ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', November 17, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nThe National Center for Education Statistics lists the following Everest Colleges and their 2015\u20132016 enrollments<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=everest&s=all|title=College Navigator \u2013 Search Results|website=nces.ed.gov|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> and accreditation status:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zenith.org/transparency-center/|title=Transparency Center \u2013 Zenith Education Group|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* Colorado Springs (CO) \u2013 209 (ACICS)\n* Thornton (CO) \u2013 232 (ACICS)\n* Orange Park (FL) \u2013 368 (ACICS)\n* Tampa (FL) \u2013 375 (ACICS)\n* Atlanta-West (GA) \u2013 467 (ACCSC)\n* Norcross (GA) \u2013 279 (ACCSC)\n* Southfield (MI) \u2013 555 (ACCSC)\n* South Plainfield (NJ) \u2013 374 (ACCSC)\n* Columbus (OH) \u2013 228 (ACCSC)\n* Henderson (NV) \u2013 417 (ACICS)\n* Arlington (TX) \u2013 390 (ACICS)\n* Fort Worth (TX) \u2013 437 (ACICS)\n* Houston-Bissonnet (TX) \u2013 590 (ACCSC)\n* Houston-Hobby (TX) \u2013 464 (ACCSC)\n* Austin (TX) \u2013 371 (ACCSC)\n* San Antonio (TX) \u2013 273 (ACCSC)\n* Chesapeake (VA) \u2013 321 (ACICS)\n* Woodbridge (VA) \u2013 342 (ACICS)\n* Everett (WA) \u2013 278 (ACICS)\n* Tacoma (WA) \u2013 278 (ACICS)\n\n==Political influence==\nFrom 2014 to 2016, [[Podesta Group]] has received at least $580,000 as the major lobbying firm for ECMC Group, Everest College's parent company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000050381&year=2015|title=Lobbying Spending Database - ECMC Group, 2015 - OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000050381&year=2014|title=Lobbying Spending Database - ECMC Group, 2014 - OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000050381&year=2016|title=Lobbying Spending Database - ECMC Group, 2016 - OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legal proceedings==\n{{Main article|Corinthian Colleges#Legal proceedings}}\n\n=== In the United States ===\n\nEverest was one of 15 for-profit colleges cited by the [[Government Accountability Office]] for deceptive or questionable statements that were made to undercover investigators posing as applicants. Two unnamed campuses were cited in this report.<ref name=\"washpostGAO\">{{Cite news\n| issn = 0740-5421\n| last = Vise\n| first = Daniel de\n|author2=Paul Kane\n| date = 2010-08-05\n| title = GAO: 15 for-profit colleges used deceptive recruiting tactics\n| work = The Washington Post\n| accessdate = 2010-08-05\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/04/AR2010080403816.html?hpid=moreheadlines\n}}</ref> [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] statistics indicated that Everest College graduates had the highest default rate of any school in California for students entering repayment in 2010<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/profit-everest-college-has-highest-student-loan-default-rate-state-5114\n|title=For-profit Everest College has highest student loan default rate in state\n|last=Perez\n|first=Erica\n|date=27 September 2010\n|work=California Watch\n|accessdate=20 November 2010\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006053056/http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/profit-everest-college-has-highest-student-loan-default-rate-state-5114\n|archive-date=6 October 2010\n|url-status=dead\n|df=dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> and the fifth highest rate in Arizona.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://azstarnet.com/news/local/education/college/article_4e04d442-4d7c-5bf8-bc52-c4dbefe3af30.html\n|title=Ariz. is worst for student loan defaults\n|last=Pallack\n|first=Becky\n|date=14 September 2010\n|work=Arizona Daily Star\n|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, a group of Everest College graduates sued the school for [[fraud]], alleging deceptive recruitment practices concerning costs of attendance, the value of the degree, and whether credits earned there would transfer to other schools.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/home/50363247-76/everest-miller-students-college.html.csp\n|title=Everest College grads sue, alleging fraud\n|last=Maffly\n|first=Brian\n|date=28 September  2010\n|work=Salt Lake Tribune\n|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Everest College in Hayward, California was issued a \"Notice to Comply\" by the [[California Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education]] for multiple violations, including engaging in \"prohibited business practices.\"<ref>[http://www.bppe.ca.gov/enforcement/actions/ntc_4300191.pdf Notice to Comply], [[California Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education]], 2012</ref>\n\n=== In Canada ===\n\nIn 2014, Everest announced the sale of all 14 locations in Canada after a probe by the parent company over concerns of falsified job placement and grades.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/all-everest-college-locations-in-canada-up-for-sale-1.2700169|title=All Everest College locations in Canada up for sale|date=8 July 2014|work=cbc.ca|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> In February 2015, Canada's National Association of Career Colleges announced that Everest College's Ontario locations had their operating license suspended by [[Ministry of Training, Colleges and Universities (Ontario)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nacc.ca/nacc-statement-everest-college-canada/|title=NACC -   NACC Statement: Everest College Canada|work=nacc.ca|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn February 19, 2015, Ontario's superintendent of private career colleges, the independent regulator that governs schools like Everest and others in the province, said it has suspended the chain's licence to operate in Ontario as a private college, effective immediately. \n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/everest-college-students-in-ottawa-share-anger-at-sudden-closure-1.2963724|title=Everest College students in Ottawa share anger at sudden closure|date=19 February 2015|work=cbc.ca|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Former students and teachers claim the college was corrupt and a scam.<ref name=everest_college_scam>{{cite news|title=Everest College closure no surprise to some who call it a scam|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/everest-college-closure-no-surprise-to-some-who-call-it-a-scam-1.2969513|accessdate=26 February 2015|agency=CBC News}}</ref> On February 20, 2015, Everest College Canada filed for Bankruptcy protection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Everest Colleges Canada, Inc. Files for Canadian Bankruptcy Protection Following Ontario Ministry Closures|url=http://www.everest.ca/|publisher=Everest College|accessdate=1 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225144750/http://www.everest.ca/|archivedate=25 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Former campuses==\n\nUnited States campuses were formerly found in the states of Arizona (2 campuses), California (15), Colorado (2), Georgia (4), Indiana (1), Illinois (5), Missouri (2), Nevada (1), Oregon (1), Texas (3), Utah (1), Virginia (3), and Washington (5).{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nEverest College of Business, Health Care and Technology formerly operated 16 campus locations in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mollyhensleyclancy/canadian-everest-campuses#.un6Zg39MK|title=Canadian Government Shuts Down Everest College Campuses|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo more campuses (Pittsburgh, PA and Aurora, CO) were closed in 2016.<ref name=\"acics.org\"/>\n\n== Corinthian debt cancellation ==\nOn June 8, 2015, the [[Department of Education]] announced that it was developing a process that would allow former students of Everest (along with other Corinthian schools) to apply for debt relief, if they believed they were victims of fraud.<ref>{{cite web|title = Fact Sheet: Protecting Students from Abusive Career Colleges {{!}} U.S. Department of Education|url = http://www.ed.gov/news/press-releases/fact-sheet-protecting-students-abusive-career-colleges|website = www.ed.gov|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref> While the Department has still not created a formal process, they have provided the outlines of what borrowers should submit if they wish to pursue debt cancellation on the Federal Student Aid website.<ref>{{cite web|title = Information About Debt Relief for Corinthian Colleges Students {{!}} Federal Student Aid|url = https://studentaid.ed.gov/sa/about/announcements/corinthian#fraud-violations-state-law|website = studentaid.ed.gov|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the advocacy group the [[Debt Collective]]<ref>{{cite web|title = The Debt Collective|url = http://debtcollective.org|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref> has created its own, unofficial \"Defense to Repayment App\" that allows former students of Corinthian and other schools accused of fraud to pursue debt cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|title = Defense to Repayment App - Debt Collective|url = https://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|website = debt-is.herokuapp.com|accessdate = 2015-09-02|first = The Debt|last = Collective|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160131074022/http://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|archive-date = 2016-01-31|url-status = dead}}</ref> The applications generated through the Debt Collective's online form was cited by the Department of Education in a Federal Register notice, which said that \"a need for a clearer process for potential claimants\" arose due to the submission of over 1000 defense to repayment claims by \"a building debt activism movement\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://ifap.ed.gov/fregisters/attachments/FR061015.pdf |title = Agency Information Collection Activities; Comment Request; Borrower Defenses against Loan Repayment |date =June 10, 2015 |accessdate = September 2, 2015|journal = Federal Register |volume=80 |issue=111 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.everest.edu/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Corinthian Colleges]]\n[[Category:Defunct universities and colleges in Canada]]\n[[Category:Former for-profit universities and colleges in Canada]]\n[[Category:Former for-profit universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Merrillville, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2007]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Everest College\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| caption = \n| latin_name = \n| other_name =          <!-- or: | other_names = -->\n| former_name =         <!-- or: | former_names = -->\n| motto = \n| motto_lang = \n| mottoeng = \n| type = non-profit career school\n| established =         {{start date|2007}} \n| closed =              <!-- {{end date|YYYY}} -->\n| founder = [[Corinthian Colleges]]\n| parent = Zenith Education Group ([[Educational Credit Management Corporation]])\n| affiliation = \n| religious_affiliation =\n| academic_affiliation =\n| endowment = \n| budget = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| chairman = \n| chairperson = \n| chancellor = \n| president = \n| vice-president = \n| superintendent = \n| provost = \n| vice_chancellor= \n| rector = \n| principal = \n| dean = \n| director = \n| head_label = \n| head = \n| academic_staff = \n| administrative_staff = \n| students = \n| undergrad = \n| postgrad = \n| doctoral = \n| other = \n| address =             <!-- Please discuss before using -->\n| city = \n| state = \n| province = \n| country = United States\n| postcode =            <!-- or: | postalcode = --><!-- or: | zipcode = -->\n| coor = \n| campus = \n| language = \n| free_label = \n| free = \n| colors =              <!-- or: | colours = -->\n| website =             {{URL|http://www.everest.edu}} \n| logo = \n| logo_size =\n| logo_alt =\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Everest College'''  is a system of colleges in the United States, and with [[Wyotech]], make up Zenith Education. It was until 2015 a system of [[for-profit college]]s in the United States and the Canadian province of Ontario, owned and operated by [[Corinthian Colleges, Inc.]] In 2015, Corinthian ceased operating and filed for bankruptcy. While most Corinthian-owned colleges were closed in early 2015, [[Educational Credit Management Corporation]] (ECMC), a non-profit, took ownership of more than half of Corinthian Colleges' campuses, including many Everest College campuses. As of 2016, 19 ECMC-owned Everest locations remain in operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everest.edu/locations/complete_list/|title=Careers Start Here - Altierus Career College|website=www.everest.edu|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> At least 10 more campuses were closed or in the process of closing in 2016.<ref name=\"acics.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acics.org/commission%20actions/content.aspx?id=1476 |title=Institution/Campus Closings |publisher=ACICS |date= |accessdate=2018-06-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/business/dp-tidewaterbiz-everest-20160408-story.html|title=Everest College in Newport News to close|first=Tara|last=Bozick|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/03/28/nonprofit-owner-former-corinthian-colleges-campuses-loses-100-million-while|title=Nonprofit owner of former Corinthian Colleges campuses loses $100 million while overhauling career college chain|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Canadian branches were not purchased by ECMC and remain closed.\n\nFollowing significant downsizing, Everest graduates still express concerns that their degrees are worthless.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pilotonline.com/trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-schools-revival/article_5e9e22de-47d2-56b5-bc6a-f37907160c5b.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316143617/http://pilotonline.com/trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-schools-revival/article_5e9e22de-47d2-56b5-bc6a-f37907160c5b.html |archive-date=2016-03-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Corinthian Colleges was compelled to pay more than $1.1 billion to the State of California, in part for defrauding thousands of students.   The judge ordered restitution of $820 million for students and civil penalties of $350 million.  According to the California State Attorney General \"For years, Corinthian profited off the backs of poor people\u2014now they have to pay. This judgment sends a clear message: There is a cost to this kind of predatory conduct.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-corinthian-colleges-judgment-false-advertising-20160323-story.html|title=Corinthian Colleges must pay nearly $1.2 billion for false advertising and lending practices|first=Matt|last=Hamilton|website=latimes.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nMore than a thousand former Everest College students have been afforded [[debt relief]] by the US government because of Everest's questionable business practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/12/04/debt-relief-some-former-corinthian-students|title=Debt Relief for Some Former Corinthian Students - Inside Higher Ed|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-85064397/|title=LA Times|website=touch.latimes.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2015/11/17/456367152/corinthian-misled-students-on-job-placement-investigation-finds|title=Corinthian Colleges Misled Students On Job Placement, Investigation Finds|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> Thousands more may get debt relief.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/education-dept-to-give-de_b_9544468.html|title=Education Dept to Give Debt Relief to More Corinthian Students|first=David|last=Halperin|date=25 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn 2007, Corinthian Colleges consolidated a number of schools under the Everest brand name. Former schools that became Everest Colleges include: [[Bryman College]], [[Ashmead College]], Mountain West College, Olympia College, [[Kee Business College]], Parks College, Western Business College, [[Blair College]] and [[Springfield College (Missouri)|Springfield College]]. In December 2007, Corinthian Colleges, Inc. (CCi) re-branded their Ontario campuses as Everest College and sold the remaining campus locations across Canada to the [[Eminata Group]].<ref>[http://investors.cci.edu/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=556063 CCI sells campuses to Eminata Group] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219224642/http://investors.cci.edu/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=556063 |date=2015-02-19 }} News Release Dec. 14, 2007</ref>\n\nIn [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], where a Corinthian Everest campus was financed with $11 million in city bonds, 25% of students found jobs and over half dropped out; the campus closed in 2012, two years after it opened.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Herzog|first1=Karen|title=University of Phoenix to close three state campuses|url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/university-of-phoenix-to-close-three-state-campuses-a379a0t-174864561.html|accessdate=19 February 2015|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=18 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prwatch.org/news/2013/07/12175/cashing-kids-139-alec-bills-2013-promote-private-profit-education-model|title=Cashing in on Kids: 139 ALEC Bills in 2013 Promote a Private, For-Profit Education Model|work=PR Watch|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe diplomas issued by Everest College were described as worthless as many graduated students found no job placement, the reputation tainted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Sophia|title=Everest College grads want loan forgiveness for 'worthless' diploma|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/everest-college-grads-want-loan-forgiveness-for-worthless-diploma-1.3036143|website=CBC News|accessdate=17 April 2015|ref=worthless_tainted}}</ref>\n\nThe Ontario government stepped in and shut down 14 Everest College of Business, Health Care and Technology campus locations owned by Corinthian Colleges on February 19, 2015. The next day, Everest College in Ontario, Canada declared bankruptcy.<ref name=everest_bankrupt>{{cite news|title=Everest College files for bankruptcy as other schools offer help|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/everest-college-files-for-bankruptcy-as-other-schools-offer-help-1.2965569|website=CBC News|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, [[Educational Credit Management Corporation]]'s subsidiary Zenith Education Group acquired 56 ''Everest College'' and [[WyoTech]] campuses from Corinthian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/02/04/guaranty-agency-buys-half-corinthian-colleges-and-forgives-480-million-student-debt|title=Guaranty agency buys half of Corinthian Colleges and forgives $480 million in student debt|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> Zenith planned to transition the schools from for-profit to nonprofit status. It also planned to eliminate some programs with poor completion and job placement rates.<ref name=\"wapo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2015/02/03/heres-how-a-debt-collector-plans-to-turn-around-failing-for-profit-colleges/|title=Here\u2019s how a debt collector plans to turn around failing for-profit colleges|last=Douglas-Gabriel|first=Danielle|date=3 February 2015 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref> Campuses with little to no revenue along with the 15 Everest campuses in California, which were not acquired by ECMC, closed their doors for good when Corinthian Colleges shuttered all of their remaining campuses on April 27, 2015.<ref name=\"kron4-0429\">{{cite news |last1=Sevilla |first1=Mario |date=April 29, 2015 |title=FAQS about Heald, Everest, And Wyotech Campuses |url=http://kron4.com/2015/04/29/faqs-about-heald-everest-and-wyotech-campuses/ |publisher=[[KRON-TV]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528155551/http://kron4.com/2015/04/29/faqs-about-heald-everest-and-wyotech-campuses |archivedate=2015-05-28 |url-status=live |accessdate=2015-06-09 |quote=[[Corinthian Colleges]] shut down all of its remaining 28 ground campuses on Monday, April 27, displacing 16,000 students. Hundreds of students were left with unfinished diplomas and loan debt. The shutdown comes less than two weeks after the [[U.S. Department of Education]] announcing it was fining the for-profit institution $30 million for misrepresentation.}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the US Department of Education fired Everest College's monitor, Hogan Marren Babbo & Rose Ltd., implicating several conflicts of interest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/news/politics/article/Trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-6888160.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322062631/http://www.sfchronicle.com/news/politics/article/Trouble-remains-following-failed-for-profit-6888160.php |archive-date=2016-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The State of California was also awarded $1.1 billion from Corinthian Colleges for false advertising and predatory business practices.<ref name=\"onebillion\">{{cite web |url=https://studentloansresolved.com/2019/03/07/everest-college-lawsuit-forgiveness-options/ |title=Everest College Lawsuit: What should borrowers know about forgiveness options |website=studentloansresolved.com |accessdate=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307192752/https://studentloansresolved.com/2019/03/07/everest-college-lawsuit-forgiveness-options/ |archive-date=7 March 2019 |date=7 March 2019}}</ref> The judge ordered restitution of $820 million for students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-86322238/|title=LA Times|website=touch.latimes.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 Associated Press investigation alleged that Everest still recruits through telemarketing, has yet to make significant changes to its shoddy curriculum. Recent graduates also reported being unable to find work that would allow them to pay their student loans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/fe5ef895b70d4b0ebecac9d5f6ab583a/trouble-remains-following-failed-profit-schools-revival|title=Trouble remains following failed for-profit schools' revival|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nApproximately 96% of Everest's funds come from the US government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/static.apps.cironline.org/doe/133.html|title=133 for-profit colleges get more than 90 percent of their revenue from taxpayers|website=s3.amazonaws.com|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> In 2016, ECMC, Everest's parent company, provided an infusion of capital to keep the schools running.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/07/28/zenith-education-gets-new-leader-250-million-it-seeks-turn-around-former-corinthian|title=Zenith Education gets a new leader, $250 million as it seeks to turn around former Corinthian programs|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Accreditation==\n\n[[Higher education accreditation in the United States|Accreditation]] for Everest College varies by country, state and region. Everest College campuses that are [[regional accreditation|regionally accredited]] are Everest College Phoenix, Everest College Mesa and online courses taught through Everest College Phoenix. All other Everest College campuses are [[Regional accreditation#Regional accreditation vs. national accreditation|nationally accredited]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everest.edu/accreditation|title=Everest: Accreditation Information|work=everest.edu|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nGenerally, credits from nationally accredited institutions are not transferable to other colleges and universities.<ref>[http://insidehighered.com/news/2007/02/26/transfer Tussling Over Transfer of Credit, ''[[Inside Higher Ed]]'', February 26, 2007 by Doug Lederman]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Everest College Phoenix was placed on academic probation by its accrediting body over concerns that it did not have enough autonomy and control over on-campus academics and operations from the parent company, Corinthian Colleges, Inc. In September 2010, the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]] rejected a recommendation from its evaluation panel that the school's accreditation be revoked outright. In November 2010 the Higher Learning Commission voted to place the campus on a \"Show-Cause\" status which will require the College to demonstrate to the commission why its accreditation should not be revoked. Everest College Phoenix had until March 2011 to respond to the request and the matter was not expected to be resolved until November 2011. The College remained an accredited institution during this period.<ref>\"[http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/business/articles/2010/11/17/20101117phoenix-everest-college-credentials-in-jeopardy.html Credentials of Everest College in jeopardy],\" ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', November 17, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nThe National Center for Education Statistics lists the following Everest Colleges and their 2015\u20132016 enrollments<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=everest&s=all|title=College Navigator \u2013 Search Results|website=nces.ed.gov|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref> and accreditation status:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zenith.org/transparency-center/|title=Transparency Center \u2013 Zenith Education Group|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n* Colorado Springs (CO) \u2013 209 (ACICS)\n* Thornton (CO) \u2013 232 (ACICS)\n* Orange Park (FL) \u2013 368 (ACICS)\n* Tampa (FL) \u2013 375 (ACICS)\n* Atlanta-West (GA) \u2013 467 (ACCSC)\n* Norcross (GA) \u2013 279 (ACCSC)\n* Southfield (MI) \u2013 555 (ACCSC)\n* South Plainfield (NJ) \u2013 374 (ACCSC)\n* Columbus (OH) \u2013 228 (ACCSC)\n* Henderson (NV) \u2013 417 (ACICS)\n* Arlington (TX) \u2013 390 (ACICS)\n* Fort Worth (TX) \u2013 437 (ACICS)\n* Houston-Bissonnet (TX) \u2013 590 (ACCSC)\n* Houston-Hobby (TX) \u2013 464 (ACCSC)\n* Austin (TX) \u2013 371 (ACCSC)\n* San Antonio (TX) \u2013 273 (ACCSC)\n* Chesapeake (VA) \u2013 321 (ACICS)\n* Woodbridge (VA) \u2013 342 (ACICS)\n* Everett (WA) \u2013 278 (ACICS)\n* Tacoma (WA) \u2013 278 (ACICS)\n\n==Political influence==\nFrom 2014 to 2016, [[Podesta Group]] has received at least $580,000 as the major lobbying firm for ECMC Group, Everest College's parent company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000050381&year=2015|title=Lobbying Spending Database - ECMC Group, 2015 - OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000050381&year=2014|title=Lobbying Spending Database - ECMC Group, 2014 - OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000050381&year=2016|title=Lobbying Spending Database - ECMC Group, 2016 - OpenSecrets|website=www.opensecrets.org|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legal proceedings==\n{{Main article|Corinthian Colleges#Legal proceedings}}\n\n=== In the United States ===\n\nEverest was one of 15 for-profit colleges cited by the [[Government Accountability Office]] for deceptive or questionable statements that were made to undercover investigators posing as applicants. Two unnamed campuses were cited in this report.<ref name=\"washpostGAO\">{{Cite news\n| issn = 0740-5421\n| last = Vise\n| first = Daniel de\n|author2=Paul Kane\n| date = 2010-08-05\n| title = GAO: 15 for-profit colleges used deceptive recruiting tactics\n| work = The Washington Post\n| accessdate = 2010-08-05\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/04/AR2010080403816.html?hpid=moreheadlines\n}}</ref> [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] statistics indicated that Everest College graduates had the highest default rate of any school in California for students entering repayment in 2010<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/profit-everest-college-has-highest-student-loan-default-rate-state-5114\n|title=For-profit Everest College has highest student loan default rate in state\n|last=Perez\n|first=Erica\n|date=27 September 2010\n|work=California Watch\n|accessdate=20 November 2010\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006053056/http://californiawatch.org/watchblog/profit-everest-college-has-highest-student-loan-default-rate-state-5114\n|archive-date=6 October 2010\n|url-status=dead\n|df=dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> and the fifth highest rate in Arizona.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://azstarnet.com/news/local/education/college/article_4e04d442-4d7c-5bf8-bc52-c4dbefe3af30.html\n|title=Ariz. is worst for student loan defaults\n|last=Pallack\n|first=Becky\n|date=14 September 2010\n|work=Arizona Daily Star\n|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, a group of Everest College graduates sued the school for [[fraud]], alleging deceptive recruitment practices concerning costs of attendance, the value of the degree, and whether credits earned there would transfer to other schools.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/home/50363247-76/everest-miller-students-college.html.csp\n|title=Everest College grads sue, alleging fraud\n|last=Maffly\n|first=Brian\n|date=28 September  2010\n|work=Salt Lake Tribune\n|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Everest College in Hayward, California was issued a \"Notice to Comply\" by the [[California Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education]] for multiple violations, including engaging in \"prohibited business practices.\"<ref>[http://www.bppe.ca.gov/enforcement/actions/ntc_4300191.pdf Notice to Comply], [[California Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education]], 2012</ref>\n\n=== In Canada ===\n\nIn 2014, Everest announced the sale of all 14 locations in Canada after a probe by the parent company over concerns of falsified job placement and grades.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/all-everest-college-locations-in-canada-up-for-sale-1.2700169|title=All Everest College locations in Canada up for sale|date=8 July 2014|work=cbc.ca|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> In February 2015, Canada's National Association of Career Colleges announced that Everest College's Ontario locations had their operating license suspended by [[Ministry of Training, Colleges and Universities (Ontario)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nacc.ca/nacc-statement-everest-college-canada/|title=NACC -   NACC Statement: Everest College Canada|work=nacc.ca|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn February 19, 2015, Ontario's superintendent of private career colleges, the independent regulator that governs schools like Everest and others in the province, said it has suspended the chain's licence to operate in Ontario as a private college, effective immediately. \n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/everest-college-students-in-ottawa-share-anger-at-sudden-closure-1.2963724|title=Everest College students in Ottawa share anger at sudden closure|date=19 February 2015|work=cbc.ca|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Former students and teachers claim the college was corrupt and a scam.<ref name=everest_college_scam>{{cite news|title=Everest College closure no surprise to some who call it a scam|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/everest-college-closure-no-surprise-to-some-who-call-it-a-scam-1.2969513|accessdate=26 February 2015|agency=CBC News}}</ref> On February 20, 2015, Everest College Canada filed for Bankruptcy protection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Everest Colleges Canada, Inc. Files for Canadian Bankruptcy Protection Following Ontario Ministry Closures|url=http://www.everest.ca/|publisher=Everest College|accessdate=1 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225144750/http://www.everest.ca/|archivedate=25 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Former campuses==\n\nUnited States campuses were formerly found in the states of Arizona (2 campuses), California (15), Colorado (2), Georgia (4), Indiana (1), Illinois (5), Missouri (2), Nevada (1), Oregon (1), Texas (3), Utah (1), Virginia (3), and Washington (5).{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nEverest College of Business, Health Care and Technology formerly operated 16 campus locations in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mollyhensleyclancy/canadian-everest-campuses#.un6Zg39MK|title=Canadian Government Shuts Down Everest College Campuses|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo more campuses (Pittsburgh, PA and Aurora, CO) were closed in 2016.<ref name=\"acics.org\"/>\n\n== Corinthian debt cancellation ==\nOn June 8, 2015, the [[Department of Education]] announced that it was developing a process that would allow former students of Everest (along with other Corinthian schools) to apply for debt relief, if they believed they were victims of fraud.<ref>{{cite web|title = Fact Sheet: Protecting Students from Abusive Career Colleges {{!}} U.S. Department of Education|url = http://www.ed.gov/news/press-releases/fact-sheet-protecting-students-abusive-career-colleges|website = www.ed.gov|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref> While the Department has still not created a formal process, they have provided the outlines of what borrowers should submit if they wish to pursue debt cancellation on the Federal Student Aid website.<ref>{{cite web|title = Information About Debt Relief for Corinthian Colleges Students {{!}} Federal Student Aid|url = https://studentaid.ed.gov/sa/about/announcements/corinthian#fraud-violations-state-law|website = studentaid.ed.gov|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the advocacy group the [[Debt Collective]]<ref>{{cite web|title = The Debt Collective|url = http://debtcollective.org|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref> has created its own, unofficial \"Defense to Repayment App\" that allows former students of Corinthian and other schools accused of fraud to pursue debt cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|title = Defense to Repayment App - Debt Collective|url = https://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|website = debt-is.herokuapp.com|accessdate = 2015-09-02|first = The Debt|last = Collective|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160131074022/http://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|archive-date = 2016-01-31|url-status = dead}}</ref> The applications generated through the Debt Collective's online form was cited by the Department of Education in a Federal Register notice, which said that \"a need for a clearer process for potential claimants\" arose due to the submission of over 1000 defense to repayment claims by \"a building debt activism movement\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://ifap.ed.gov/fregisters/attachments/FR061015.pdf |title = Agency Information Collection Activities; Comment Request; Borrower Defenses against Loan Repayment |date =June 10, 2015 |accessdate = September 2, 2015|journal = Federal Register |volume=80 |issue=111 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.everest.edu/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Corinthian Colleges]]\n[[Category:Defunct universities and colleges in Canada]]\n[[Category:Former for-profit universities and colleges in Canada]]\n[[Category:Former for-profit universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Merrillville, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Private universities and colleges in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2007]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Everest_College"}
{"title_page": "Mary L. Walker", "text_new": "[[File:Mary L Walker.jpg|thumb|right|Mary L. Walker]]\n'''Mary Walker''' (born December 1, 1948) is an American [[lawyer]] who served as a high-ranking appointee under Presidents Ronald Reagan, George H.W. Bush and George W. Bush.\n\n==Private Law Practice and Government Career==\n\nMary L. Walker was born in [[Dayton, Ohio]] on December 1, 1948.<ref name=\"utexas1985\">[http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/speeches/1985/91885d.htm Ronald Reagan: Nomination of Mary L. Walker To Be an Assistant Secretary of Energy, Sept. 18, 1985]</ref> She was educated at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], receiving an [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] in Biological Sciences in 1970.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She then attended both UCLA Law School and [[Boston University School of Law]], receiving a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] in 1973.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/>\n\nWalker joined the legal department of the [[Southern Pacific Transportation Company]] in San Francisco in 1973.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She worked there until 1976 when she joined the [[law firm]] of Richards, Watson, Dreyfuss & Gershon in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She was made a partner in 1979, working there until 1982.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/>\n\nIn 1982, Walker accepted an appointment in the [[United States Department of Justice]] as Principal Deputy Assistant Attorney General in the Land and Natural Resources Division.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> From 1984 to 1985, she was the Deputy Solicitor of the [[United States Department of the Interior]].<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> On September 18, 1985, [[President of the United States]] [[Ronald Reagan]] nominated her to be Assistant Secretary of Energy (Environment, Safety, and Health).<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She was confirmed by the Senate and held this office until 1988.<ref name=\"findarticles1\">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0RBE/is_2004_Annual/ai_n8569467/ Walker Military Biography]</ref>\n\nShe spent 1988-89 as Vice President of Law Environmental Inc.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/> She was a partner at Richards, Watson & Gershon and their managing partner in [[San Francisco]] from 1989 to 1991.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/> She was a partner of [[Luce, Forward, Hamilton & Scripps]] in [[San Diego]] from 1991 to 1994, and then a partner at [[Brobeck, Phleger & Harrison]] in San Diego from 1994 to 2001.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/>\n\nShe was also a U.S. Commissioner on the [[Inter-American Tropical Tuna Commission]] from 1988 to 1995, a Presidential Appointment.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/>\n\nAn [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]], Walker co-founded the Professional Women's Fellowship in San Diego, a group related to [[Campus Crusade for Christ]].\n\nOn September 26, 2001, President [[George W. Bush]] nominated Walker to be [[General Counsel of the Air Force]]. She was confirmed by the Senate and held this office for the duration of the [[presidency of George W. Bush]]. As of 2009, she is the longest-serving General Counsel in the history of the Department of the Air Force. During her tenure there, she received many awards for her service.\n\n[[File: US Air Force (USAF) General Counsel Mary L. Walker, holds a copy of the report on the US Air Force Academy (USAFA) sexual misconduct study released June 19th during a Pentagon press briefing 030619-F-FC975-085.jpg|thumb|Mary L. Walker, holds a copy of the report on the US Air Force Academy (USAFA) sexual misconduct study]]\n\n==Post Government Career==\n\nWalker returned to private practice in 2009 and, as an independent contractor, provides legal services to private clients and law firms.<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/marylwalker/</ref> She also began a career as a published author of historical fiction under the pen name Regan Walker.<ref>http://www.reganwalkerauthor.com/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nWalker is divorced and has one son. She lives in San Diego.\n\n==Role in the Detainee Interrogation Controversy==\n\nOn January 15, 2003, as a result of concern expressed by the Army that more techniques were needed to interrogate the terrorists being held at Guantanamo, the [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Donald Rumsfeld]] ordered a review of what additional techniques might be available and permissible under law. Two days later, [[William J. Haynes, II]], the [[General Counsel]] of the [[United States Department of Defense]] designated Walker as the head of a departmental working group tasked with implementing the Secretary's request.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/documents/011703haynes.pdf Memo From the Pentagon Counsel to the General Counsel for the Air Force, Jan. 17, 2003]</ref> Walker established a committee of the senior lawyers in the Pentagon, both military and civilian, and a career-level working group having expertise in the substantive issues and additional techniques to be given legal and policy review.\n\nThe next week, Walker received an extensive legal memorandum, written in 2001, from the [[Office of Legal Counsel]] of the U.S. Department of Justice, authored by [[John Yoo]] and signed by [[Jay Bybee]], the head of the [[Office of Legal Counsel]]. She was advised by William J. Haynes, General Counsel of the Department of Defense, that this legal analysis would be controlling. As the two working groups proceeded to conduct their review, on January 23, 2003, [[General Counsel of the Navy]] [[Alberto J. Mora]], a member of the senior legal group, reviewed a hard copy of that memorandum in Walker's office<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tortureaccountability.org/mary_walker |title=Mary Walker Profile, CTA |access-date=2011-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227102743/http://tortureaccountability.org/mary_walker |archive-date=2014-12-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (copies were not made widely available pursuant to instructions of William J. Haynes, General Counsel of the Department of Defense).<ref name=\"historycommons1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker |title=From History Commons |access-date=2011-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014318/http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker |archive-date=2016-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  This led to a disagreement between Mora and the senior legal group. Mora disagreed with the reasoning of the Department of Justice, whereas Walker agreed with Yoo's reasoning concerning the powers of the President.<ref>[http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker From History Commons] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014318/http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker |date=2016-03-05 }},</ref> Walker encouraged discussion among the legal team and invited Yoo to the Pentagon to answer their questions, which he did on two occasions. Walker also encouraged Mora to share his views and to meet with General Counsel Haynes. Mora met with Haynes and circulated an opposing draft memo. Haynes did not accept Mora's views, nor did any members of the senior legal committee.\n\nOn March 6, 2003, by a unanimous vote, all members of the senior legal group (including the Navy) presented their recommendations for new techniques to Secretary Rumsfeld. These had been proposed by the technical working group and were subject to legal and policy review by the senior legal team. The recommendations to Secretary Rumsfeld stated that the reasoning behind the Department of Justice memorandum was sound, although the group expressly stated it did not need to rely upon the more far-reaching conclusions of the Justice Department's memorandum concerning the powers of the President. The final report was presented on April 4, 2003. Secretary Rumsfeld adopted the vast majority of the new techniques proposed. At the Administration's request, the Justice Department subsequently reviewed the Working Group's recommendations that were adopted by Secretary Rumsfeld and fully endorsed them.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walker, Mary L.}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:General Counsels of the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category:George W. Bush administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]\n[[Category:War on Terror]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Dayton, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mary L Walker.jpg|thumb|right|Mary L. Walker]]\n'''Mary Walker''' (born December 1, 1948) is an American [[lawyer]] who served as a high-ranking appointee under Presidents Ronald Reagan, George H.W. Bush and George W. Bush.\n==Private Law Practice and Government Career==\n\nMary L. Walker was born in [[Dayton, Ohio]] on December 1, 1948.<ref name=\"utexas1985\">[http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/speeches/1985/91885d.htm Ronald Reagan: Nomination of Mary L. Walker To Be an Assistant Secretary of Energy, Sept. 18, 1985]</ref> She was educated at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], receiving an [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] in Biological Sciences in 1970.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She then attended both UCLA Law School and [[Boston University School of Law]], receiving a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] in 1973.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/>\n\nWalker joined the legal department of the [[Southern Pacific Transportation Company]] in San Francisco in 1973.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She worked there until 1976 when she joined the [[law firm]] of Richards, Watson, Dreyfuss & Gershon in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She was made a partner in 1979, working there until 1982.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/>\n\nIn 1982, Walker accepted an appointment in the [[United States Department of Justice]] as Principal Deputy Assistant Attorney General in the Land and Natural Resources Division.<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> From 1984 to 1985, she was the Deputy Solicitor of the [[United States Department of the Interior]].<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> On September 18, 1985, [[President of the United States]] [[Ronald Reagan]] nominated her to be Assistant Secretary of Energy (Environment, Safety, and Health).<ref name=\"utexas1985\"/> She was confirmed by the Senate and held this office until 1988.<ref name=\"findarticles1\">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0RBE/is_2004_Annual/ai_n8569467/ Walker Military Biography]</ref>\n\nShe spent 1988-89 as Vice President of Law Environmental Inc.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/> She was a partner at Richards, Watson & Gershon and their managing partner in [[San Francisco]] from 1989 to 1991.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/> She was a partner of [[Luce, Forward, Hamilton & Scripps]] in [[San Diego]] from 1991 to 1994, and then a partner at [[Brobeck, Phleger & Harrison]] in San Diego from 1994 to 2001.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/>\n\nShe was also a U.S. Commissioner on the [[Inter-American Tropical Tuna Commission]] from 1988 to 1995, a Presidential Appointment.<ref name=\"findarticles1\"/> \n\nAn [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]], Walker co-founded the Professional Women's Fellowship in San Diego, a group related to [[Campus Crusade for Christ]].\n\nOn September 26, 2001, President [[George W. Bush]] nominated Walker to be [[General Counsel of the Air Force]]. She was confirmed by the Senate and held this office for the duration of the [[presidency of George W. Bush]]. As of 2009, she is the longest-serving General Counsel in the history of the Department of the Air Force. During her tenure there, she received many awards for her service.\n\n[[File: US Air Force (USAF) General Counsel Mary L. Walker, holds a copy of the report on the US Air Force Academy (USAFA) sexual misconduct study released June 19th during a Pentagon press briefing 030619-F-FC975-085.jpg|thumb|Mary L. Walker, holds a copy of the report on the US Air Force Academy (USAFA) sexual misconduct study]]\n\n==Post Government Career==\n\nWalker returned to private practice in 2009 and, as an independent contractor, provides legal services to private clients and law firms. <ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/marylwalker/</ref> She also began a career as a published author of historical fiction under the pen name Regan Walker. <ref>http://www.reganwalkerauthor.com/</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\n\nWalker is divorced and has one son. She lives in San Diego.\n\n==Role in the Detainee Interrogation Controversy==\n\nOn January 15, 2003, as a result of concern expressed by the Army that more techniques were needed to interrogate the terrorists being held at Guantanamo, the [[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[Donald Rumsfeld]] ordered a review of what additional techniques might be available and permissible under law. Two days later, [[William J. Haynes, II]], the [[General Counsel]] of the [[United States Department of Defense]] designated Walker as the head of a departmental working group tasked with implementing the Secretary's request.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/documents/011703haynes.pdf Memo From the Pentagon Counsel to the General Counsel for the Air Force, Jan. 17, 2003]</ref> Walker established a committee of the senior lawyers in the Pentagon, both military and civilian, and a career-level working group having expertise in the substantive issues and additional techniques to be given legal and policy review.\n\nThe next week, Walker received an extensive legal memorandum, written in 2001, from the [[Office of Legal Counsel]] of the U.S. Department of Justice, authored by [[John Yoo]] and signed by [[Jay Bybee]], the head of the [[Office of Legal Counsel]]. She was advised by William J. Haynes, General Counsel of the Department of Defense, that this legal analysis would be controlling. As the two working groups proceeded to conduct their review, on January 23, 2003, [[General Counsel of the Navy]] [[Alberto J. Mora]], a member of the senior legal group, reviewed a hard copy of that memorandum in Walker's office<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tortureaccountability.org/mary_walker |title=Mary Walker Profile, CTA |access-date=2011-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227102743/http://tortureaccountability.org/mary_walker |archive-date=2014-12-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (copies were not made widely available pursuant to instructions of William J. Haynes, General Counsel of the Department of Defense).<ref name=\"historycommons1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker |title=From History Commons |access-date=2011-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014318/http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker |archive-date=2016-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  This led to a disagreement between Mora and the senior legal group. Mora disagreed with the reasoning of the Department of Justice, whereas Walker agreed with Yoo's reasoning concerning the powers of the President.<ref>[http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker From History Commons] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014318/http://www.historycommons.org/entity.jsp?entity=mary_walker |date=2016-03-05 }},</ref> Walker encouraged discussion among the legal team and invited Yoo to the Pentagon to answer their questions, which he did on two occasions. Walker also encouraged Mora to share his views and to meet with General Counsel Haynes. Mora met with Haynes and circulated an opposing draft memo. Haynes did not accept Mora's views, nor did any members of the senior legal committee. \n\nOn March 6, 2003, by a unanimous vote, all members of the senior legal group (including the Navy) presented their recommendations for new techniques to Secretary Rumsfeld. These had been proposed by the technical working group and were subject to legal and policy review by the senior legal team. The recommendations to Secretary Rumsfeld stated that the reasoning behind the Department of Justice memorandum was sound, although the group expressly stated it did not need to rely upon the more far-reaching conclusions of the Justice Department's memorandum concerning the powers of the President. The final report was presented on April 4, 2003. Secretary Rumsfeld adopted the vast majority of the new techniques proposed. At the Administration's request, the Justice Department subsequently reviewed the Working Group's recommendations that were adopted by Secretary Rumsfeld and fully endorsed them.\n\n==References==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walker, Mary L.}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category: Living people]]\n[[Category: University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category: General Counsels of the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category: George W. Bush administration personnel]]\n[[Category: Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]\n[[Category: War on Terror]]\n[[Category: Women in the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category: Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category: Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category: People from Dayton, Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_L._Walker"}
